Data analysis workflow (40 minutes)

Based on my experience, this workflow will help you be effective

  • Read : Read data into R
  • Explore : Explore data using graphs and tables
  • Assume : Identify assumptions for the analysis
  • Analyze : Analyze data based on objectives and proposed methods
  • Assess : Assess results based on assumptions. Identify limitations of analysis
  • Present : Present results, data and codes

Below, is another workflow, proposed by Hadley in his book.

Data visualization

Introduction

Data visualization is defined as the graphical representation of information and data.

How to perform data visualization? We will be using visual elements such as:

  • charts
  • graphs
  • maps

Data visualization tools provide an accessible way to see and understand trends, outliers, and patterns in data.

Objective of data visualization: data visualization tools and technologies are used to analyze massive amounts of information and make data-driven decisions.

Figures :

  • A figures is a visual presentation of results. Come in the form of graphs, charts, drawings, photos, or maps. They provide visual impact and can effectively communicate your primary finding.

Plot:

  • A plot is a graphical technique for representing a data set Usually as a graph showing the relationship between two or more variables. The plot can be drawn by hand or by a computer.

Graphs:

  • A graph is a picture designed to express words Particularly the connection between two or more quantities.

Basic plots

Histogram
ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_histogram(aes(lifeExp))
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Barchart

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_bar(aes(continent))

Line graph

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_line(aes(x = year, y = lifeExp, group = country))

Scatter plot

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_point(aes(x = gdpPercap, y = lifeExp))

Split your plots

ggplot(gapminder) +
  geom_histogram(aes(lifeExp)) +
  facet_wrap(~ continent)
`stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Data wrangling

Introduction

Remember, dataset contains data. Data contains variables in tabular format. There are:

  • Variables in columns
  • Observations in rows

Definition : Data are characteristics or information usually numerical that are collected through observation.Data is a set of values of qualitative or quantitative variables They are about one or more persons or objects, while a datum (singular of data) is single value of a single variable.

Definition : variable is any characteristics, number, or quantity that can be measured or counted.

Types of variables:

  • Numeric
  • Categorical

Categorical variables

  • have values that describe a âqualityâ or âcharacteristicâ of a data unit

  • may be further described as ordinal or nominal

  • such as an ordinal variable has values that can be logically ordered or ranked.

  • Size : small, medium, large, extra large

  • Attitudes : strongly agree, agree, disagree, strongly disagree

A nominal variable has no logical sequence. For example:

  • Sex : male, female
  • Business type : insurance, healthcare, retail
  • Race : Asian, Caucasian, African

Hands-on

Data wrangling or transformation

Useful package

  • tidyverse package is collection of packages, specifically the dplyr package. It is a very useful package to munge or wrangle or to tranform your data.

Common procedures

The common procedures that data analyst does include:

  1. reducing the size of dataset by selecting certain variables (or columns)
  2. generating new variable from existing variables
  3. sorting observation of a variable
  4. grouping observations based on certain criteria
  5. reducing variable to groups to in order to estimate summary statistic

Some functions

  1. dplyr::select() - to select a number of variables from a dataframe
  2. dplyr::mutate() - to generate a new variable from existing variable
  3. dplyr::arrange() - to sort observation of a variable
  4. dplyr::filter() - to group observations that fulfill certain criteria
  5. dplyr::group_by() and dplyr::summarize() - to reduce variable to groups in order to provide summary statistic

Create a new project or set your working directory

This only applies if you work on RStudio IDE on your machine.

  • It is very important to ensure you know where your working directory is
  • To do so, the best practice is is to create a new project
  • Create a RStudio project everytime you want to start new analysis (but not when you want redo them)

Create a new project

Steps:

  1. File
  2. New Project
  3. New Directory
  4. New Project
  5. Choose Directory (folder)

The project directory is the directory (folder) where you store datasets, R codes and other outputs

Working directory

If you do not start with a new project, you still need to know the location of your working directory?.

  1. to use R project to work with your data or analysis
  2. if you are not using R project, make sure you are inside the correct working directory.
  3. Type getwd() to display the active working directory. And to set a working directory use setwd().
  4. once you are know where your working directory is, you can start read or import data into your working directory.

Packages to read data

  • Remember, there are a number of packages you can use to read the data into R.

  • It depends on the format of your data.

  • Some useful packages to read data

    • haven package
    • foreign package
    • readr package
    • readxl package

Data format

  1. readr package provides a fast and friendly way to read rectangular data (like csv, tsv, and fwf).
  2. readxl package reads .xls and .xlsx sheets.
  3. haven package reads and writes SPSS, Stata, and SAS data.

With dplyr::mutate(), you can generate new variable.

For example, in the dataset mysw, we want to create a new variable named as bmi.

This variable equals mass in kg divided by squared height (in meter)

\[bmi = \frac{kg}{m^2}\]

  • Now, your dataset mysw has 5 columns (variables).
  • The last variable is bmi
mysw <- mysw %>% 
  mutate(bmi = mass/(height/100)^2)
mysw

dplyr::filter()

Here, we will create a new dataset (which we will name as mysw_m_40) that contains observations with these criteria:

  • gender is male AND
  • bmi at or above 40
mysw_m_40 <- mysw %>% 
  filter(gender == 'male', bmi >= 40)
mysw_m_40
# A tibble: 0 Ã 6
# â¹ 6 variables: name <chr>, gender <chr>, height <int>, mass <dbl>, bmi <dbl>,
#   bmisq <dbl>

Next, we will create a new dataset (named as mysw_ht_45) that contain

  • height above 200 OR BMI above 45, AND
  • does not include NA (which is missing value) observation for bmi
mysw_ht_45 <- mysw %>% 
  filter(height >200 | bmi >45, bmi != 'NA')
mysw_ht_45

Categorize a numerical variable

mysw <- mysw %>%
  mutate(cat_bmi = cut(bmi, 
                       breaks = c(0, 20, 30, 50, 500),
                       labels = c('0-19', '20-29', 
                                  '30-49', '50-500')))
table(mysw$cat_bmi)

  0-19  20-29  30-49 50-500 
    13     34     10      2

Regroup a categorical variable

mysw <- mysw %>% 
  mutate(cat_bmi2 = recode(cat_bmi,
                           '0-19' = 'less than 30',
                           '20-29' = 'less than 30',
                           '30-49' = '30 or above',
                           '50-500' = '30 or above')) 
table(mysw$cat_bmi2)

less than 30  30 or above 
          47           12

More complicated dplyr verbs

To be more efficent, use multiple dplyr functions in one line of R code

  • select()
  • group_by()
  • summarize()

Think of the results:

desc_sw <- starwars %>% 
  filter(sex == "male", height > 100, mass > 100) %>% 
  select(height, mass, species) %>%
  group_by(species) %>%
  summarize(mean_ht = mean(height, na.rm = TRUE), 
            mean_mass = mean(mass, na.rm = TRUE),
            freq = n())

Epidemiological analysis

The workflow and codes for this section come largelyt from The Epidemiologist R Handbook

Objectives

We will generate an epidemic curve.

Loading packages

Now, we will use a different function pacman::p_load(). This function will load the libraries. If the libraries are not installed, then they will be installed. But you have to be connected to the internet.

pacman::p_load(
  rio,          # file import/export
  here,         # relative filepaths 
  lubridate,    # working with dates/epiweeks
  aweek,        # alternative package for working with dates/epiweeks
  incidence2,   # epicurves of linelist data
  i2extras,     # supplement to incidence2
  stringr,      # search and manipulate character strings
  forcats,      # working with factors
  RColorBrewer, # Color palettes from colorbrewer2.org
  tidyverse     # data management + ggplot2 graphics
)

Import data

Statistical modelling: Scalar or continuous outcome (20 minutes)

Introduction

Objectives:

At the end of this section, you will be to

  • model continuous outcome variable using multiple linear regression
  • perform model assessment
  • interpret model

Regression analysis helps us

  • to explain relationship between variables
  • to estimate the effect of a set of variables (predictors) onto another variable (the outcome)
  • to make inference â how large the effect?
  • to predict the outcome based on new data

Estimation and inference are different.

  • To estimate: A process by which one makes inferences about a population, based on information obtained from a sample.
  • To infer : To make reasons involved in drawing a conclusion or making a logical judgment on the basis of circumstantial evidence and prior conclusions and not only on the basis of direct observation

Hands-on

Objectives

In this short practicals, we will show how to perform estimation, inference, prediction and model checking for linear regression model.

Model checking

We need to check for linear model assumptions

  1. Linearity of residuals
  2. Residuals are normally distributed
  3. Equal variance of residuals
  4. Independence observations
plot(modldl.gender.ia)

Somethings are not right

  • does not look random
  • some outliers
  • is it linear?

We need to do further treatment:

  • transformation of variables
  • more complex model
  • removing of influential observations

Questions and Tips

  • what function did we use to estimate a lm model?
  • what is another function we can use?
  • Model specification is important
  • Which variables are
    • confounders
    • mediators
    • moderators
  • Effect of multicolinearity
  • Model checking and model assessment
  • Are there outliers and are they influentials?
  • Simple model vs complex model, which will you prioritize?
  • Bias and variance
  • Exploratory vs Confirmatory model

Statistical modelling: Binary outcome (20 minutes)

Motivation

When outcome is binary, the common analysis for making inference or prediction is logistic regression.

What are the aims?

  • To explain vs to predict
  • In statistics, to explain is more common: Interested in the beta
  • In analytics, to predict is more common: Not interested in beta, but interested to predict the outcome

Questions:

  • Give example of outcome relevant to your area that you may study
  • State the objective of the analysis
  • Are the data suitable for logistic regression analysis?

When the outcome is categorical (in the form of binary), we model using logistic regression. Examples of binary outcome

  • Acceptance of loan = Accepted vs Rejected
  • Loan defaulters = Yes vs No

Binary logistic regression models, for example :

  • Acceptance of loan <- gender + age + job status + â¦.
  • Loan defaulters <- age + income + amount of loan + â¦..

The logit model is written as:

\[log \frac{p}{1-p} = \beta_0 + \beta_{age} + \beta_{male} + \beta_{chinese} + \beta_{indians} + \beta_{age}\times\beta_{male}\]

Multivariables logistic regression

Let us run a multivariable model with

  • Outcome: oc2
  • Primary variables: ASA, degree of perforation, PULP, NSAIDS, Hg, onset more than 24
  • Confounding variables: age, gender, diabetes

Primary variables are variables of interest that would predict outcome of peptic ulcer. Confounding variables are variables that may alter the effect of the primary variables when they are in the model. This may happen due to different distribution of them at the beginning of the study.

Only control baseline variables (refer to Andrew Gelman argument)

model_multivar <- glm(oc2 ~ age + gender + epigastric_pain + 
                        onset_more_24_hrs + diabetes + NSAIDS + 
                        factor(ASA) + PULP + perforation + hemoglobin, 
                      family = binomial(link = 'logit'), 
                      data = PUP2)

Let add an interaction term, assuming that the effect of covariates on outcome maybe different according to different level of PULP and extent of perforation size. So the interaction effect is between perforation and PULP.

model_ia <- glm(oc2 ~ age + gender + epigastric_pain + 
                  onset_more_24_hrs + diabetes + NSAIDS + 
                  factor(ASA) + PULP + perforation + 
                  hemoglobin + perforation:PULP, 
                family = binomial(link = 'logit'), data = PUP2)

Then store as a tidy object

model_ia <- tidy(model_ia, conf.int = T)

And now we export the table in csv format for easy manipulation in MS Excel for example:

write_csv(model_ia, 'model_ia.csv')

Model checking

Making predictions

  • log-odds
  • probability
fitted_logodds <- augment(model_multivar, type.predict = 'link')
fitted_prob <- augment(model_multivar, type.predict = 'response')

Questions and Tips

  • What function did we use to perform logistic regression?
  • What statistical framework did we use to perform the logistic regression? What statistical family did we choose for estimation?
  • How to assess logistic regression model?
    • confusion matrix
    • overall model fitness (Hosmer Lemeshow test)
    • Area under the ROC curve
  • Model diagnostics for outliers and influential cases

Summary

Useful for users and trainers:

  1. Draft your data analysis workflow
  2. Identify each stage of the workflow
  3. At each stage, ask
  • what task is involved
  • what R functions required to perform the task
  • which R package that contains the function
  1. Perform the task using the default parameters
  2. Tweak the function to suit more complex task
  3. If errors committed, get help
  • friends
  • StackOverflow
  • R community
  1. Use tools
  • Posit Cloud
  • RStudio IDE
  • Google Collab
  1. Traditional stat software may not able to handle the demand of modern-wide-big-on-the-cloud data
  2. Practice, practice, practise
